1. Create a GitHub Repository:

Go to GitHub and sign in to your account.
Click the plus sign (+) in the top right corner and select "New repository."
Give your repository a descriptive name (e.g., "regex-matcher-app").
Add a brief description.
Choose a repository license (e.g., MIT).
Click "Create repository."
2. Initialize Git in Your VS Code Project:

Open your VS Code project folder.
Open the terminal in VS Code (Ctrl+` or View -> Terminal).
Run the following command to initialize Git in your project:
Bash
git init
Use code with caution.

3. Add Files to Git:

In the terminal, run the following command to add all files in your project to Git:
Bash
git add .
Use code with caution.

4. Commit Changes:

In the terminal, run the following command to commit the added files:
Bash
git commit -m "Initial commit"
Use code with caution.

Replace "Initial commit" with a meaningful commit message.
5. Connect to GitHub Repository:

In VS Code, open the Source Control panel (Ctrl+Shift+G).
Click the "Publish" button in the Source Control panel.
Enter the URL of your GitHub repository (e.g., https://github.com/your_username/regex-matcher-app.git).
Click "Publish."
6. Push Changes to GitHub:

In the Source Control panel, you should see a message indicating that the repository has been published.
Click the "Sync" button to push your local changes to the remote GitHub repository.